15 f. The example of Circe is well chosen. The poet prays that

tas et . . . color: modest youth's fresh color.

Canidia like the early sorceress will reverse her spell.-—saetosa: tle. with swinish bristles. —duris pellibus : abl. with exuere. — labori- osi: Homeric πολύτλας, πολυτλή- μων; best taken with Ulixei. Stin, cf. 16, 60.

17 f. mens: Horace supposes that Circe's victims lost their minds as well as shapes, but in the Ho- meric account their fate is made the more pathetic because their wits remain. —- sonus z voice.— honor: in contrast to the ugly swinish faces they had just put off.
